==English==

===Etymology===
From {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|þunor|lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{term/t|gem-pro|*þunraz}}, from *þen, from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{term/t|ine-pro|*(s)tenh₂-||to thunder}}. Germanic cognates include West Frisian {{term|tonger|lang=fy}}, Dutch {{term|donder|lang=nl}}, German {{term|Donner|lang=de}}. Other cognates include [[w:Persian language|Persian]] {{term|تندر|tr=tondar|lang=fa}}, Latin {{term|tonō|lang=la}}.

===Pronunciation===
* {{a|UK}} {{IPA|/ˈθʌn.də/}}
* {{a|US}} {{enPR|thŭn'dər}}, {{IPA|/ˈθʌn.dɚ/}}
* {{audio|en-us-thunder.ogg|Audio (US)}}
* {{rhymes|ʌndə(ɹ)}}

===Noun===
{{wikipedia}}
{{en-noun|~}}

# The [[sound]] caused by the discharge of atmospheric electrical charge.
#: '''''Thunder''' ''is preceded by [[lightning]].''
# A sound resembling thunder.
# A deep, [[rumble|rumbling]] noise.
#: ''Off in the distance, he heard the '''thunder''' of hoofbeats, signalling a stampede.''
# An alarming or startling [[threat]] or [[denunciation]].
#* Prescott
#*: The '''thunders''' of the Vatican could no longer strike into the heart of princes.
# {{context|obsolete|lang=en}} The [[discharge]] of [[electricity]]; a [[thunderbolt]].
#* Shakespeare
#*: The revenging gods / 'Gainst parricides did all their '''thunders''' bend.
# {{context|figuratively|lang=en}} The [[spotlight]].

